title: CPF Contribution Rates by Age – Overview
text:
# LastChecked: 2025-11-23

## Overview
Employees and employers contribute a percentage of monthly wages to CPF. The total contribution rate depends mainly on the employee’s age and wage band, and is shared between employer and employee.

## Key points
- Contribution rates are highest for younger workers and step down gradually with age.
- For Singapore Citizens and SPRs (from the third year onwards), CPF publishes a standard table of rates by age group.
- Policy changes gradually raise contribution rates for older workers to strengthen retirement adequacy.

title: CPF Contribution Rates by Age – Overview
text:
## Age bands (illustrative description)
- **55 and below** – highest total contribution rate.
- **Above 55 to 60** – slightly lower total rate, with scheduled increases from 2025/2026.
- **Above 60 to 65** – lower total rate, also subject to scheduled increases.
- **Above 65** – lower rates reflecting shorter remaining working horizon.

## Movements between age bands
- When an employee crosses specific birthdate thresholds (e.g. 55, 60, 65, 70), the applicable contribution rate changes.
- The new rate applies from the first day of the month after they enter the new age band.

title: CPF Contribution Rates by Age – Overview
text:
## Relation to the simulator
- For the prototype, the app may use a simplified mapping from income band and age band to an estimated monthly contribution.
- This estimate is for illustration only and may not match the member’s actual contributions.

## Notes
- For actual payroll calculations, employers must refer to CPF’s official tables and tools.
- This summary is meant only to give users a sense of how contributions support long-term retirement savings.

title: CPF LIFE – Overview and Payouts
text:
# LastChecked: 2025-11-23

## Overview
CPF LIFE is Singapore’s national longevity insurance scheme. It provides monthly payouts for as long as a member lives, funded by savings in their Retirement Account and government-guaranteed interest.

## Key features
- Lifelong monthly payouts starting from a chosen payout age within CPF’s allowed range.
- Payouts continue even after the original RA savings are exhausted.
- Any unused CPF LIFE premium balance, together with remaining CPF savings, will be paid to beneficiaries when the member passes away.

title: CPF LIFE – Overview and Payouts
text:
## CPF LIFE plans (high level)
- **Standard Plan** – relatively higher payouts at the start and stable levels over time.
- **Escalating Plan** – lower payouts initially that gradually increase each year, helping offset inflation.
- **Basic / other variants** – may have different payout patterns or premium balances.


## How payouts are determined (simplified)
- Size of your Retirement Account savings used to join CPF LIFE.
- Choice of plan and payout start age.
- CPF interest rates, including extra interest paid on lower balances.
- Mortality and longevity assumptions used by CPF’s actuaries.

CPF provides payout ranges for different retirement sum levels and age cohorts in its examples, and offers calculators to estimate payouts more precisely.

title: CPF LIFE – Overview and Payouts
text:
## Official tools
- **Monthly Payout Estimator** – lets you estimate payouts based on savings and chosen payout age.
- Other planners and calculators may be available for members below 55 or those already on a plan.

## Notes
- This summary is for educational use; it omits many actuarial and policy details.
- Members should use CPF’s official estimators and planning tools for individual calculations.

title: CPF Interest and Extra Interest – Overview
text:
# LastChecked: 2025-11-23

## Overview
CPF pays interest on members’ savings at government-guaranteed rates. In addition to base interest on each account, extra interest is paid on lower balances to help build up retirement savings, especially for older members.

## Base interest (high level)
- Ordinary Account (OA) earns a base interest rate with a long-term floor.
- Special, MediSave and Retirement Accounts (SA, MA, RA) earn a higher base rate with their own floor.
- Interest is typically computed monthly and credited annually.

title: CPF Interest and Extra Interest – Overview
text:
## Extra interest
- Members below 55 earn an extra interest on the first portion of their combined CPF balances, up to a cap for OA.
- Members 55 and above earn higher extra interest on the first tier of combined balances, and additional extra interest on the next tier.
- Extra interest earned on OA savings is usually directed to SA or RA to further strengthen retirement savings.

## Why this matters
- Extra interest boosts the long-term growth of CPF savings, especially for smaller balances.
- For retirement planning, this means that CPF often provides a relatively stable, risk-free return, but actual returns depend on account composition and policy changes.

title: CPF Interest and Extra Interest – Overview
text:
## Notes
- CPF announces interest rates for specific quarters and may update them from time to time.
- Always refer to the latest official announcements for current rates and extra interest rules.

title: MediSave – Healthcare Uses and Limits
text:
# LastChecked: 2025-11-23

## Overview
MediSave is a key part of the CPF system that helps members save for healthcare needs. Members can use MediSave to pay for approved medical expenses, insurance premiums, and selected outpatient treatments.

## What MediSave can be used for
- Hospitalisation and day surgery.
- Selected outpatient treatments.
- Approved chronic disease management programmes.
- Certain health screenings and vaccinations.

## Limits
- Withdrawals are subject to MediSave withdrawal limits (per bill, per item, or per year).
- Limits ensure members continue to have adequate healthcare savings over time.

title: MediSave – Healthcare Uses and Limits
text:
## Relation to retirement
- Though not directly part of retirement income, MediSave reduces the burden of medical expenses in older age.
- Understanding MediSave helps users make sense of how CPF accounts serve different needs.

## Notes
- MediSave rules can be updated; users must refer to official CPF pages for exact limits.

title: CPF Payout Start Age and Deferring Payouts
text:
# LastChecked: 2025-11-23

## Overview
Members can choose when to begin receiving monthly CPF LIFE payouts, within the payout start age range set by CPF. Deferring payouts can increase monthly payout amounts.

## Payout start age (high level)
- Most members begin receiving payouts at the **standard payout age**.
- Members may choose to defer payouts up to a maximum age set by CPF.

## Why defer payouts?
- Delaying payouts allows RA savings more time to grow.
- Monthly payouts will be higher when started later.
- Members with other income sources early in retirement may prefer to defer.

title: CPF Payout Start Age and Deferring Payouts
text:
## Relation to the simulator
- Members who seem below FRS may benefit from considering a later payout age.
- Simulator explanations may highlight the effect of extra interest over a longer accumulation period.

## Notes
- Differences in payout amounts depend on CPF LIFE actuarial calculations.
- Members should always check with the official CPF payout estimator for exact numbers.

title: Property Ownership and Its Impact on Retirement Sums
text:
# LastChecked: 2025-11-23

## Overview
Property ownership can affect how much CPF members must set aside for retirement. In particular, members who own a home with sufficient remaining lease may be allowed to use the Basic Retirement Sum (BRS) instead of the Full Retirement Sum (FRS) at age 55.

## Key points
- Members who own a property with a lease long enough to last them until age 95 may rely on BRS.
- If the lease does not meet requirements, members may have to meet FRS instead.
- Members can “pledge” their property when forming their Retirement Account (RA), allowing partial withdrawal above the BRS.

title: Property Ownership and Its Impact on Retirement Sums
text:
## Property pledge
- A portion of the property’s value may be pledged to CPF when withdrawing beyond BRS.
- If the property is later sold, the pledged amount (plus accrued interest) must be returned to CPF up to the amount withdrawn.

## Impact on withdrawals at 55
- Property owners who meet conditions can withdraw more at 55, depending on their RA formation amount.
- Non-property owners must generally meet FRS before withdrawing amounts above the basic threshold.

## Notes
- Property rules interact with CPF retirement rules in complex ways.
- Members should refer to CPF housing pages and specific calculators for details.

title: CPF Retirement Sums (BRS, FRS, ERS) – Core Policy
text:
# LastChecked: 2025-11-23

## Overview
CPF sets three benchmark retirement sums – Basic (BRS), Full (FRS) and Enhanced (ERS) – to indicate how much savings a member should set aside at age 55 to receive different levels of monthly payouts in retirement.

## Key definitions
- **BRS**: Baseline amount that aims to cover basic living expenses in retirement, assuming the member owns a property with sufficient lease.
- **FRS**: Standard benchmark (about twice BRS) for members who do not rely on property to support their retirement income.
- **ERS**: Higher benchmark (historically around three times BRS; from 2025 it may be raised further) for members who want higher payouts and can afford to set aside more.

title: CPF Retirement Sums (BRS, FRS, ERS) – Core Policy
text:
## Cohort-based sums
- The retirement sums are set based on the year a member turns 55.
- Once your cohort's sum is set, it does not change for that member.
- CPF publishes tables showing BRS, FRS and ERS for recent cohorts.

## How the sums are used
- At age 55, OA and SA savings are combined into the Retirement Account (RA).
- Members are expected to set aside at least the BRS or FRS, depending on property ownership and lease conditions.
- Savings above the required sum may be withdrawn in cash, subject to CPF rules.

title: CPF Retirement Sums (BRS, FRS, ERS) – Core Policy
text:
## Relationship to CPF LIFE and payouts
- Retirement sums give an indication of the monthly payout range members might receive under CPF LIFE.
- Actual payouts depend on the member's exact RA balance, payout age, and chosen CPF LIFE plan.
- Members should use official CPF calculators to estimate payouts for their own situation.

## Notes
- This document summarises CPF's explanation of BRS, FRS and ERS as of 2025.
- Exact dollar values and policies are updated periodically by CPF.
- Always refer to the latest information on CPF’s official website.

title: Retirement Account (RA) Top-Ups and Boosting Retirement Payouts
text:
# LastChecked: 2025-11-23

## Overview
CPF allows members (and their loved ones) to top up the Retirement Account (RA) to increase retirement payouts. Top-ups can be made via the Retirement Sum Topping-Up (RSTU) scheme or CPF transfers. These top-ups help members reach higher retirement sums such as the Full Retirement Sum (FRS) or Enhanced Retirement Sum (ERS).

## Why people top up
- To enjoy **higher CPF LIFE monthly payouts** in the future.
- To help parents, grandparents, or spouses increase their retirement adequacy.
- To earn risk-free CPF interest rates on long-term savings.
- To utilise spare cash that’s intended for retirement.

title: Retirement Account (RA) Top-Ups and Boosting Retirement Payouts
text:
## Types of top-ups
### Cash top-ups (RSTU)
- Anyone can top up their own RA.
- You can also top up your parents’, grandparents’, spouse’s or siblings’ CPF accounts.
- Cash top-ups typically count towards tax relief (subject to prevailing caps and rules).

### CPF transfers
- Members can transfer savings from SA or OA to RA (the member’s own RA only).
- Transfers earn the higher interest rate applicable to RA.
- Transfers are **not** eligible for tax relief.

## How much can be topped up
- Members can top up up to the **Enhanced Retirement Sum (ERS)**.
- ERS is typically around three times the Basic Retirement Sum (BRS).  
  (Exact amounts are cohort-based and set at age 55.)

title: Retirement Account (RA) Top-Ups and Boosting Retirement Payouts
text:
## Impact on retirement payouts
- Top-ups directly increase the RA balance.
- Higher RA balances result in **higher CPF LIFE monthly payouts**.
- Top-ups help close the gap for members who are below BRS/FRS.

## Notes
- Top-ups are **non-refundable** except under special limited circumstances.
- Tax rules and eligibility for relief can change; members should check the latest CPF guidance.
- This summary is simplified for educational purposes.

title: Withdrawing CPF Savings from Age 55
text:
# LastChecked: 2025-11-23

## Overview
From age 55, members can start withdrawing part of their CPF savings. The amount depends on whether they have set aside their required retirement sum and whether they own a property that qualifies for using the Basic Retirement Sum.

## Key withdrawal rules (high level)
- At 55, part of your OA and SA is set aside in the Retirement Account (RA) up to your required sum.
- Members can withdraw a small lump sum even if they have not met the Full Retirement Sum.
- Members who have set aside the required sum may withdraw savings above it, subject to CPF rules.

title: Withdrawing CPF Savings from Age 55
text:
## Typical scenarios
- **Members who have not met the Full Retirement Sum (FRS)**  
  - Can usually withdraw up to a limited amount (e.g. a fixed basic amount) from 55.
  - Remaining savings are mostly kept in CPF to earn interest and support payouts later.

- **Members who have set aside at least the FRS**  
  - May withdraw savings above the FRS from their OA and SA.
  - Withdrawals will reduce future monthly payouts.

title: Withdrawing CPF Savings from Age 55
text:
- **Property owners using BRS**  
  - Members who meet criteria (including property lease) can use the Basic Retirement Sum instead of FRS.
  - They may withdraw more cash if their property is pledged and conditions are met.
  - When the property is sold, part of the sale proceeds may need to be refunded to CPF (principal plus accrued interest) to restore retirement savings.

## Daily withdrawal limit and channels
- Online withdrawals for members 55 and above are typically subject to a daily limit to manage security and fraud risk.
- Members can adjust their daily withdrawal limit within CPF’s allowed range.
- Withdrawals can usually be made via online services, selected forms, or other official channels indicated on CPF’s site.

title: Withdrawing CPF Savings from Age 55
text:
## Interaction with payouts
- Money withdrawn at 55 reduces the amount left in CPF to generate interest and fund CPF LIFE payouts.
- Members who do not need the cash immediately may benefit from leaving savings in CPF to grow.

## Notes
- This summary simplifies CPF’s detailed rules on withdrawals from age 55.
- Actual withdrawal eligibility and amounts depend on your RA balance, property status, and other factors.
- Always refer to CPF’s official tools and services for up-to-date withdrawal options.

title: CPF Withdrawal Process – Application Steps & Daily Limits
text:
# LastChecked: 2025-11-23

## Overview
Members who are 55 and above can withdraw eligible CPF savings through CPF’s online services or designated channels. Withdrawals may be subject to daily limits and require proper verification for security.

## Daily withdrawal limit (overview)
- Online withdrawals are subject to a **default daily limit** (varies depending on CPF's prevailing security policy).
- Members may adjust their daily limit within CPF’s allowed range using online services.
- Limits help safeguard against unauthorised or fraudulent withdrawals.

title: CPF Withdrawal Process – Application Steps & Daily Limits
text:
## Withdrawal channels
### Online application
- Members log in with Singpass.
- Withdrawals can typically be made from OA and SA (subject to age 55 rules), and RA (from the payout eligibility age).
- Funds are disbursed to members’ bank accounts.

### In-person or form-based applications
- Some special withdrawal types may require forms or additional supporting documents.
- Processing time may vary by withdrawal type.

## Typical process flow
1. Log in to CPF online services.  
2. Select the withdrawal type (55 withdrawal, payouts, medical needs, etc.).  
3. Verify bank account details.  
4. Confirm amount (subject to eligibility and limits).  
5. Submit and wait for CPF processing and bank transfer.

title: CPF Withdrawal Process – Application Steps & Daily Limits
text:
## Important conditions
- Withdrawals reduce future RA balances and therefore future CPF LIFE payouts.
- Members should understand how withdrawal choices affect long-term retirement income.
- CPF may ask for additional identity verification depending on transaction risk.

## Notes
- This summary simplifies withdrawal procedures and may not cover all special cases.
- Members must always follow CPF’s official instructions and use verified channels.
